 ways in which Jihadi groups and their supporters use visualisation, sound production and aesthetic means to articulate their cause in online as well as offline contexts.Divided into four thematic sections, the chapters probe Jihadi appropriation of traditional and popular cultural expressions and show how, in turn, political activists appropriate extremist media to oppose and resist the propaganda. By conceptualising militant Islamist audiovisual productions as part of global media aesthetics and practices, the authors shed light on how religious actors, artists, civil society activists, global youth, political forces, security agencies and researchers engage with mediated manifestations of Jihadi ideology to deconstruct, reinforce, defy or oppose the messages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aDigital mediaxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aInternet and terrorism. 0aTerrorismxReligious aspectsxIslam. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aART / Art & Politics.2bisacsh1 aAli, Rami, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeese, Yorck, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Carin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarvalho, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDick, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuhrmann, Larissa-Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaspar, Hande Abay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGünther, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJunk, Ju